# Standing Debug & Deploy Policy

## MinyanPays screens (minyanpays.com)

Numbered list matches `apps/web/src/App.tsx` routes and pre-route shells. Base URL: `https://minyanpays.com`.

1. **App loading** — full-page spinner while org list loads (no path yet).
2. **Empty locations** — message when no organizations exist (dev/setup); same shell as org flow, no slug selected.
3. **Choose location** — org picker (`OrgPicker`) when locations exist but none selected yet (no React Router path; before main app shell).
4. **`/`** — redirects to `/punch` (no standalone UI).
5. **Punch menu** — `https://minyanpays.com/punch` — check-in/out hub.
6. **Punch in** — `https://minyanpays.com/punch/in` — public check-in (phone + PIN).
7. **Punch out** — `https://minyanpays.com/punch/out` — public check-out (phone + PIN).
8. **Admin login** — `https://minyanpays.com/admin`.
9. **Admin change password** — `https://minyanpays.com/admin/change-password` — forced first-time password change.
10. **Admin dashboard** — `https://minyanpays.com/admin/app` — hub (today, member, rabbi, location) + modals.
11. **Rabbi login** — `https://minyanpays.com/rabbi`.
12. **Rabbi dashboard** — `https://minyanpays.com/rabbi/app` — tabs (today, members, payouts, banner) + member edit overlay.
13. **Member hub** — `https://minyanpays.com/member` — join / view member entry.
14. **Member login** — `https://minyanpays.com/member/login`.
15. **Member signup** — `https://minyanpays.com/member/signup`.
16. **Member dashboard (balance)** — `https://minyanpays.com/member/app`.
17. **Member profile** — `https://minyanpays.com/member/profile`.
18. **Member billing** — `https://minyanpays.com/member/billing`.
19. **Unknown path** — any other path redirects to `/punch` (catch-all).

*Note:* Admin and Rabbi dashboards open **modals/overlays** (add/edit member, rabbi, location, etc.) without changing the URL — regression tests should exercise those flows from screens **10** and **12**.

When fixing a UI or flow issue:

- Re-test **similar** numbered screens (same shell: punch trio, member trio, auth pair, dashboards with bottom nav).
- For layout/scroll/bottom-nav issues, spot-check **5–7**, **13–18**, **10**, and **12** at minimum.
- Confirm: page scroll works, bottom content is reachable, controls are not hidden by fixed nav, and defaults/autofill are correct.
- **iPhone (Safari / PWA):** cold-open each numbered screen **1–19** (and open modals on **10** / **12**). Expect **no horizontal overflow** on first paint, **no “too tall until rotate/resize”** layout, and **scroll to the true bottom** so the last control is not under the fixed bottom nav (use safe-area + padding assumptions in `App.tsx` / `index.css`).

When a new recurring issue is discovered:

- Append it under `Debugging issues` in `docs/PROGRAMMER_HANDOFF.md`.
- Add a short entry in `PROJECT_STATUS.md` with what changed and what to re-test next.

Daily testing-mode doc hygiene:

- In testing mode (daily cadence), review active docs before ending work:
  - `docs/PROGRAMMER_HANDOFF.md`
  - `docs/AI_VERIFICATION_CHECKLIST.md`
  - `docs/COPILOT_GEMINI_REVIEW_INSTRUCTIONS.md`
  - `PROJECT_STATUS.md`
- Remove or merge duplicate debugging bullets; keep one canonical wording per issue.
- If a doc is redundant, mark it as reference/archival and point to the canonical file instead of copying content.

Commit hygiene policy:

- If changes are substantial, propose a commit.
- If there are many edits (around 10+ files) or long elapsed time (~1 hour), remind to checkpoint with a commit.
- Never auto-push without explicit user instruction.

## Production deploy runbook (AI does this, not the user)

Render's free tier has **no Shell and no SSH** (see `docs/RENDER_DEPLOYMENT.md`). The AI must drive deploys through `git push` + `render.yaml` rather than handing instructions back to the user.

### What the AI is allowed to do without asking

1. Edit, commit, and push code, including temporary changes to `render.yaml`.
2. Push to **both** remotes: `origin` (canonical, Render-connected) **and** `cur` (mirror).
3. Probe production via the public REST API at `https://minyan-pays.onrender.com/api/...` to verify deploys, schema, and feature behavior.
4. Use the production admin/rabbi REST API to create or update Rabbi, Shamosh, and Organization records once the user has supplied (or already documented) the admin password.

### What the AI must ask the user for

- Production secrets the AI cannot derive: `ADMIN_PASSWORD` for each org slug, the Render Postgres `External` URL (only if a direct DB action is required), and confirmation before changing or removing any Render env var.
- Approval before destructive actions: dropping a column, deleting org/user data, force-pushing.

### Standard deploy flow (no schema change)

1. `git status` to confirm clean working tree, then `git push origin main` and `git push cur main`.
2. Wait for Render rebuild (typical 2-4 min) and probe `GET /api/health` until `{ ok: true }`.
3. Run a feature-level probe relevant to the change (a route that didn't exist before, or that depends on the new code path).

### Schema-change deploy flow (Prisma `db push` with potential data loss)

Render's API service builds with `npx prisma db push` (no flag). If the schema change introduces a new `@unique`, drops a column, or otherwise trips Prisma's data-loss guard, the build aborts. To migrate **without** human intervention, the AI uses the temporary-flag dance:

1. **Set the flag.** Edit `render.yaml`'s API `buildCommand` to use `npx prisma db push --accept-data-loss`. Add a comment noting it's one-time.
2. **Push.** Commit + push to `origin/main` and `cur/main`. Render auto-deploys.
3. **Wait & verify.** Poll a route that exercises the new schema (e.g. for a new column on `Rabbi`, `POST /api/auth/rabbi` with bogus credentials should return **401**, not **500**).
4. **Revert the flag.** Edit `render.yaml` back to `npx prisma db push` (no flag). Commit + push. The next build is a no-op for schema but restores the safety guard.
5. **Document.** Update `PROJECT_STATUS.md`'s "Current Task / Goal" and `docs/RENDER_DEPLOYMENT.md`'s **Migration log** with the date, schema delta, and the two commit SHAs (the flag-on commit and the revert).

> Never leave `--accept-data-loss` in `render.yaml` after the migration succeeds. It defeats Prisma's main protection against accidental column drops.

### Direct production DB access (only if the flag dance is not enough)

If a needed migration cannot be expressed as a `db push` (e.g. data backfill across rows), the AI must:

1. Ask the user for the **External** `DATABASE_URL` from the Render Postgres dashboard.
2. From `apps/api`, run `DATABASE_URL=<external> npx prisma db push` or a one-off script (e.g. `node apps/api/scripts/<name>.mjs`).
3. Delete (or `.gitignore`) any local file that contains the URL before committing anything.

### Configuring Rabbis / Shamoshim post-deploy

After a multi-rabbi schema deploy the AI drives the per-org setup over the REST API rather than walking the user through clicks:

```text
# 1. Admin login
POST /api/auth/admin   { organizationSlug, password }   -> { token }

# 2. Per location: set/refresh structured address (and auto-geocode)
PATCH /api/admin/settings (Bearer admin)
  { locationAddress, locationCity, locationState, locationPostalCode,
    locationPhone, autoGeocode: true }

# 3. List existing rabbis at the location
GET /api/admin/rabbis (Bearer admin)

# 4. For each rabbi: flip Main + assign a generated 8-alphanumeric password
GET   /api/admin/passwords/generate (Bearer admin) -> { password }
PATCH /api/admin/rabbis/:id (Bearer admin) { isMain: true, password }

# 5. (Optional) Create additional rabbis
POST /api/admin/rabbis (Bearer admin) { name, isMain: false, generatePassword: true, ... }

# 6. Log in as that rabbi to add Shamoshim
POST /api/auth/rabbi (organizationSlug, the new rabbi password) -> { token, rabbiKind: "MAIN" }
POST /api/rabbi/shamoshim (Bearer rabbi) { name, phone, generatePassword: true }
```

The AI must surface every generated password back to the user **once in chat**. Plaintext is also stored on the row for the admin UI, but the chat reply is the user's only out-of-band copy at the moment of generation.

### After a successful migration

- Rotate or remove the legacy `RABBI_PASSWORD` env var on Render only after every org has at least one rabbi with `isMain: true` and a `passwordPlain`. **Confirm with the user before removing.**
- Append a one-line entry to `docs/RENDER_DEPLOYMENT.md` "Migration log" with date + schema delta + commits.

### Failure handling

- If a Render build fails, ask the user to paste the Render build log (free tier exposes logs only via the dashboard). Do not silently retry.
- If post-deploy probes return 500, immediately push a revert commit on `origin/main` to roll back to the previous SHA, then debug locally before re-attempting.
